---
// src/components/chrome/Drawer.astro — M-UX T7 deliverable.
//
// Mobile-drawer overlay support: a backdrop element + a JS island
// that toggles `body.drawer-open` so the SAME `<aside data-slot=
// "left-rail">` rendered by `<LeftRail slot="left-rail" />` becomes
// a slide-in drawer at <1024px. Per ADR-0002 + architecture.md §1.6
// (Page chrome — Mobile (<1024px) — single column / left rail
// collapses to hamburger drawer in the breadcrumb bar).
//
// **Cycle 2 refactor (2026-04-25 — closes M-UX-T7-ISS-02 + ISS-03).**
// Cycle 1 twice-rendered LeftRail (a desktop instance in the left-
// rail slot + a drawer instance in this Drawer's <slot />). That
// produced duplicate `id="cs300-completion-indicator"` /
// `id="cs300-completion-indicator-data"` per chapter route (HTML5
// invalid; ISS-03) and inflated dist/client/ by ~700 KB driven by
// the doubled CompletionIndicator JSON payload (ISS-02). Cycle 2
// collapses the two LeftRail mounts into ONE: the existing
// `<LeftRail slot="left-rail" />` IS the drawer at <1024px. CSS in
// `Base.astro` repositions the SAME aside as a `position: fixed`
// element off-canvas at <1024px, sliding it into view when
// `body.drawer-open` is set. Single DOM tree → no duplicate IDs,
// no duplicate JSON payload, ~700 KB recovered.
//
// **What this component now renders:**
//   1. The drawer backdrop element (`<div id="drawer-backdrop">`).
//      Stays at body level (mounted via `Base.astro`'s `slot=
//      "drawer"`) so its `position: fixed; z-index: 9998` paints
//      across the full viewport without inheriting the sticky-
//      breadcrumb stacking context.
//   2. The JS island (inline `<script>`). Listens for
//      `cs300:drawer-toggle` from `DrawerTrigger.astro`, toggles
//      `body.drawer-open` + `aria-hidden` on the existing left-rail
//      aside, manages focus trap targeting that same aside, manages
//      Escape / backdrop-click / link-click close paths.
//
// **What this component no longer renders:**
//   - The drawer aside element. The aside that becomes the drawer
//     IS the existing `<aside data-slot="left-rail">` rendered by
//     `Base.astro`. Stretched into a fixed off-canvas element at
//     <1024px via Base.astro CSS rules. Single DOM tree.
//   - A drawer-internal `<slot />`. Cycle 1 had one to host the
//     duplicate `<LeftRail />`; cycle 2 deletes it because the
//     route files no longer pass children to <Drawer>.
//   - A drawer-close button. The drawer-trigger hamburger doubles
//     as the close affordance: it's the focus-restore target on
//     close, and `aria-expanded` on it reflects open/closed state.
//     A separate close button inside the drawer was a cycle 1
//     additive that became redundant once the aside IS the drawer
//     (the aside has no "header" of its own — just the chapter list).
//
// **Two-component split (preserved from cycle 1).**
// `Drawer.astro` (this file) + `DrawerTrigger.astro` (sibling)
// remain split because the trigger button must mount inside
// `Breadcrumb.astro`'s `drawer-trigger` slot, while the backdrop
// must mount at body level via Base.astro's `slot="drawer"`. A
// single Astro component cannot route to two parent slots.
// Communication via `cs300:drawer-toggle` CustomEvent — no shared
// state, no JS-to-JS imports.
//
// **Behaviour contract** (per T7 spec Step 1):
//   - Click trigger → `body.drawer-open` set; backdrop fades in;
//     left-rail aside slides in (CSS in Base.astro); trigger's
//     `aria-expanded="true"`; aside's `aria-hidden="false"`; focus
//     moves into the drawer (first focusable inside the aside).
//   - Click backdrop OR press Escape → reverse: classes removed,
//     aria-* flipped, focus restored to the trigger button.
//   - Click any link inside the drawer → same close path
//     (navigating to a chapter dismisses the drawer naturally).
//   - Focus trap: while open, Tab cycles through focusables inside
//     the aside; first ↔ last wrap around. Shift+Tab reverses.
//
// **JS island sizing** (per T7 spec line 58): native DOM APIs only,
// no framework. Inline `<script>` (Astro hoists into the shared
// chunk).
//
// **No animation framework**: native CSS transitions only. Slide-
// in is `transform: translateX(...)` + transition (rules live in
// Base.astro alongside the rest of the breakpoint-specific layout).
// Backdrop fade is `opacity` + transition (rules in this file).
//
// **z-index discipline**: aside z-index 9999 (Base.astro), backdrop
// 9998 (this file). Body-level fixed-position siblings
// (AnnotateButton, MarkReadButton, interactive-badge — all
// z-index: 1000) are CSS-suppressed by `body.drawer-open` rules in
// Base.astro so the open drawer is never occluded.
//
// **Static-mode posture.** The drawer + trigger render in both
// modes; SSR drawer-list is the static-mode mobile chapter-nav.
// CompletionIndicator stays inside LeftRail (as it was in T2),
// gated on `data-interactive-only` for the checkmarks; it now
// renders ONCE per page (not twice), which IS the cycle 2 fix.
//
// Companion files:
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_polish/tasks/T7_mobile_drawer.md
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_polish/issues/T7_issue.md
//     (M-UX-T7-ISS-02 + ISS-03 — closed by cycle 2)
//   - design_docs/adr/0002_ux_layer_mdn_three_column.md
//   - src/layouts/Base.astro (CSS rules that turn the existing
//     `aside[data-slot="left-rail"]` into the drawer at <1024px)
//   - src/components/chrome/Breadcrumb.astro (drawer-trigger slot)
//   - src/components/chrome/DrawerTrigger.astro (the hamburger)
//   - src/components/chrome/LeftRail.astro (zero-diff vs cycle 1;
//     the existing left-rail content IS the drawer at <1024px)
---

<div
  id="drawer-backdrop"
  class="drawer-backdrop"
  data-drawer-backdrop
  aria-hidden="true"
  hidden
></div>

<style>
  /* Tokens come from src/styles/chrome.css (imported globally by
     Base.astro). The backdrop is hidden by default at every viewport
     via the `hidden` attribute; CSS only governs the fade transition
     once JS removes `hidden` and adds `.open`. */
  .drawer-backdrop {
    position: fixed;
    inset: 0;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
    opacity: 0;
    transition: opacity 200ms ease;
    z-index: 9998;
  }

  .drawer-backdrop[hidden] {
    /* Browser default for `[hidden]` is `display: none` — when the
       backdrop is fully closed (post-transition), keep it removed
       from the layout entirely. The JS island removes `hidden`
       BEFORE adding `.open` so the fade-in transition runs. */
    display: none;
  }

  .drawer-backdrop.open {
    opacity: 1;
  }
</style>

<script>
  /**
   * Drawer JS island (M-UX T7, cycle 2 refactor).
   *
   * Cycle 2 simplification: the drawer aside IS the existing
   * `<aside data-slot="left-rail">` rendered by Base.astro. This
   * island no longer manages a separate aside element — it manages
   * `body.drawer-open` (which CSS in Base.astro reads to slide the
   * left-rail aside into view) plus `aria-*` state on the aside
   * itself, the backdrop element, and the trigger button.
   *
   * Native DOM APIs only — no framework, no animation library.
   * Inline `<script>` so the trigger is interactive on first paint.
   *
   * State lives entirely on the DOM (`body.drawer-open` class +
   * `aria-expanded` on trigger + `aria-hidden` on aside + `.open`
   * on backdrop). No JS module-level state; multiple identical
   * page-loads cannot diverge.
   *
   * Communication with `DrawerTrigger.astro` (sibling) flows
   * through a `cs300:drawer-toggle` CustomEvent. Same idiom as
   * every other M3 / M-UX inter-island contract.
   */

  // The drawer aside IS the existing left-rail. Base.astro renders
  // it at body level (well, inside .chrome) with the
  // `data-slot="left-rail"` attribute; we query by that selector so
  // we don't depend on a specific id. Falls back to a no-op guard
  // if the aside is missing (e.g. index page, where there's no
  // drawer to open in the first place).
  const aside = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
    'aside[data-slot="left-rail"]',
  );
  const backdrop = document.getElementById('drawer-backdrop');

  if (aside && backdrop) {
    /**
     * Tracks the element that had focus before the drawer opened so
     * we can restore on close. Falls back to the trigger button if
     * focus was somewhere unexpected.
     */
    let lastFocused: HTMLElement | null = null;

    /**
     * Resolve the focusable elements inside the drawer aside at the
     * time of trap evaluation. Re-queried on every Tab press so any
     * late-injected content (e.g. CompletionIndicator paint) is
     * included.
     */
    function focusables(): HTMLElement[] {
      if (!aside) return [];
      return Array.from(
        aside.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>(
          'a[href], button:not([disabled]), [tabindex]:not([tabindex="-1"])',
        ),
      ).filter((el) => !el.hasAttribute('hidden') && el.offsetParent !== null);
    }

    function open(): void {
      if (!aside || !backdrop) return;
      lastFocused = document.activeElement as HTMLElement | null;
      backdrop.hidden = false;
      // Force a reflow before adding `.open` so the fade-in
      // transition runs from the initial `opacity: 0` state rather
      // than skipping straight to opacity 1.
      void backdrop.offsetWidth;
      backdrop.classList.add('open');
      aside.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'false');
      document.body.classList.add('drawer-open');
      const trigger = document.getElementById('drawer-trigger');
      trigger?.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
      // Move focus into the drawer for the focus-trap loop. Pick
      // the first focusable element inside the aside (typically the
      // first chapter link). Predictable + immediately accessible.
      const items = focusables();
      items[0]?.focus();
    }

    function close(): void {
      if (!aside || !backdrop) return;
      backdrop.classList.remove('open');
      aside.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');
      document.body.classList.remove('drawer-open');
      const trigger = document.getElementById('drawer-trigger');
      trigger?.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
      // Restore focus to whatever was focused before the drawer
      // opened — typically the trigger button.
      const restore = lastFocused ?? document.getElementById('drawer-trigger');
      // Hide-after-transition so the slide-out animation can run
      // before the backdrop disappears from the layout. 200ms
      // matches the CSS transition duration on both backdrop opacity
      // and aside transform.
      window.setTimeout(() => {
        if (backdrop && !backdrop.classList.contains('open')) {
          backdrop.hidden = true;
        }
      }, 200);
      restore?.focus();
    }

    function toggle(): void {
      if (document.body.classList.contains('drawer-open')) {
        close();
      } else {
        open();
      }
    }

    // Trigger contract — DrawerTrigger.astro fires this event on
    // click. No detail payload (open if closed, close if open).
    window.addEventListener('cs300:drawer-toggle', toggle as EventListener);

    // Backdrop click closes the drawer.
    backdrop.addEventListener('click', close);

    // Escape closes; Tab cycles focus inside the drawer aside.
    document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      if (!document.body.classList.contains('drawer-open')) return;
      if (e.key === 'Escape') {
        e.preventDefault();
        close();
      }
      if (e.key === 'Tab') {
        const items = focusables();
        if (items.length === 0) return;
        const first = items[0];
        const last = items[items.length - 1];
        const active = document.activeElement as HTMLElement | null;
        if (e.shiftKey) {
          if (active === first || !aside.contains(active)) {
            e.preventDefault();
            last.focus();
          }
        } else {
          if (active === last || !aside.contains(active)) {
            e.preventDefault();
            first.focus();
          }
        }
      }
    });

    // Clicking any link inside the drawer aside closes it (so
    // navigating to a chapter dismisses the drawer naturally).
    aside.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
      // Only react when the drawer is open — at desktop, the aside
      // is the static left-rail and link clicks are normal nav
      // without any close behaviour to run.
      if (!document.body.classList.contains('drawer-open')) return;
      const target = e.target as HTMLElement | null;
      if (target && target.closest('a[href]')) {
        close();
      }
    });
  }
</script>
